SIMPLE: sley
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sley
<hw>Sley</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>sl<?/</ets>,
fr. <ets>sle⟦aacute⟧n</ets> to strike. See <er>Slay</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A weaver's reed.</def> <altsp>[Spelt
also <asp>slaie</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A guideway in a knitting machine.</def>
<rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Weaving)</fld> <def>The number of ends per inch in
the cloth, provided each dent in the reed in which it was made contained
an equal number of ends.</def> <rj><au>E. Whitworth.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sley</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sley
<hw>Sley</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To separate or part the threads of,
and arrange them in a reed; -- a term used by weavers. See
<er>Sleave</er>, and <er>Sleid</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slibber</ent>⟦br⟧
